WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.800
This is Twit.

00:00:02.760 --> 00:00:07.120
Being in the print industry, we get hundreds of jobs coming through,

00:00:07.179 --> 00:00:11.339
and you have to review each one and figure out what's going on with it,

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:13.779
and is the file set up correctly and those kind of things.

00:00:13.820 --> 00:00:17.199
And I was always looking for ways to automate that process.

00:00:17.559 --> 00:00:22.239
So I got into, you know, working with Quark extension developers,

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.059
and that helped automate it some.

00:00:26.059 --> 00:00:38.299
But then in 1993, I saw an ad in the Apple developer brochure about this amazing English-like language that could control the action of the computers and the apps that are on it.

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:47.439
So I sent in the money and I paid an extra $15 for a scriptable finder, which came on like a 400K floppy, right?

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:49.619
Was this from Apple or a third party?

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:50.679
This was from Apple.

00:00:50.679 --> 00:01:01.140
And so I got the AppleScript disk, and at that time, the app that was really powerful, that was scriptable, was QuarkXPress.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:02.899
Which was used for page layout.

00:01:03.179 --> 00:01:03.539
Yes.

00:01:03.759 --> 00:01:06.000
It took over from PageMaker.

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:06.219
Yeah, pretty much took over.

00:01:06.219 --> 00:01:10.780
All this PageMaker was the dominant program, but right about that time, Quark kind of took over.

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:18.099
Dave Shaver and Ralph Risch had implemented Apple Event Scripting, AppleScript, in QuarkXPress with Tim Gill's help.

00:01:18.299 --> 00:01:18.439
Right.

00:01:18.439 --> 00:01:25.120
right And so I remember it was in the evening, was after the day and I was sitting there alone

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:30.040
at night and I'm going through this, trying to figure out what this is all about. And it says,

00:01:30.159 --> 00:01:36.159
okay, there's a dictionary and this should be called a box. And then, okay, it has properties.

00:01:36.159 --> 00:01:41.140
All right. So I write my first script. So I selected a box. And you've not been a programmer

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:46.459
in the past. No, no programming at all. no programming at all. And I drew out a box and

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:57.219
was set the color of the current box to blue you remember it i remember it it's infused in my brain

00:01:57.219 --> 00:02:05.540
and i ran that and that box changed Boing and i really yeah yes at that point i let go all my

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:11.719
clients i would had a business doing you know desktop publishing design business and i let go

00:02:11.719 --> 00:02:16.740
all my clients and i just focused on learning everything i could possibly learn about AppleScript

00:02:18.439 --> 00:02:22.500
that just because you loved it or did you see a like you see how it could be used what was it

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:32.639
that got you it it hit a profound concept within me it opened up a profound concept that has stayed

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:38.759
with me my entire professional life which is that the power of the computer should reside

00:02:38.759 --> 00:02:45.680
in the hands of the one using it i don't have to go to a developer and say please can you make this

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:53.599
so that this does this or can you alter your application so that i can do this it put all that

00:02:53.599 --> 00:03:02.240
power in my hands and for me that was an awakening and after that i started developing automation

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:08.860
around the print industry because i was in it and i expanded out into other industries too like

00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:15.879
media production and video production to automate them. And Apple noticed me because I was writing

00:03:15.879 --> 00:03:21.280
books on the topic and I'd be at the same trade shows as them. And my audience would be the Apple

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:25.240
employees standing there watching this. Because they probably didn't know all the things you could

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:30.159
do with this stuff. There was maybe a handful of guys that knew it was in the system, but they

00:03:30.159 --> 00:03:35.319
would stand there and eventually they started to ask me, would I join? And I said, well, why should

00:03:35.319 --> 00:03:42.919
I'd join. I'd take a 50% pay cut to work for you. I don't want to do that. And then over a period of

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:53.139
time, about a year, it was a group effort by Shafaa Syed, Bamandara, and Guy Kawasaki, and a

00:03:53.139 --> 00:04:00.560
couple other people, and Chris Espinoza. They got me on board at Apple, and I joined at like the

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:09.259
worst time. Steve had left. Yeah, I joined in January of 97. So Apple had the word beleaguered

00:04:09.259 --> 00:04:17.220
tattooed. This is the beleaguered years. And if you look at where I was hired, I was hired in

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:24.319
January. And at one point, Apple put out these boards on campus that all the employees could see

00:04:24.319 --> 00:04:30.279
had a list of every Apple employee and when in order of their hiring. And so there was like

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:35.920
boards around campus and everybody was walking around looking for their name, right? And I was

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:42.540
over here like on board number two. And if you look after my name, then it's like Craig Feguerini

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:49.120
and Avi and all the next guys. Yeah. So I was like the last hire, one of the last hires

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:59.319
before everything opened up. And so automation to me came from a very personal basis. I was always

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:08.019
from the the aspect of getting stuff done in the real world and that knowledge about what

00:05:08.019 --> 00:05:16.060
customers needed and how it gets used in the end was essential to my role at Apple when i came on

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:22.660
board to you know to protect this technology because at that time Apple script was not

00:05:22.660 --> 00:05:24.420
part of the operating system

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:31.879
you

